<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1902-04-14T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1902-04-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="710" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d710">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hill</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Buck</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-04-14"><hi rend="italic">April 14,
                                1902</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 400.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                            dispatch No. 027, of the 18th ultimo, confirming your telegram of the
                            preceding night in relation to the proposal of the Japanese Government
                            to arbitrate the question of the tax on buildings erected on lands held
                            by perpetual leases in the former foreign settlements in Japan.</p>
                        <p>The Department approves your view that you ought not to ask that the
                            United States be included as one of the powers to participate in the
                            arbitration proceedings, unless so instructed.</p>
                        <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">David J. Hill</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Acting Secretary.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>